<TEXT>
the energy department under pressure from 
environmental critics will give the public a chance to review how 
its plans to clean up and rebuild the nations nuclear weapons 
complex will affect the environment 
the announcement friday by energy secretary james d watkins 
came nearly seven months after 22 environmental and arms control 
groups sued the department to force such a review 
the significance of it is that it would be the first 
comprehensive and public analysis of the whole weapons program 
said dan reicher an attorney for the natural resources defense 
council one of the environmental groups that sued 
reicher said allowing the public to participate in the planning 
could lead to significant changes in the future emphasis of the 
multibillion dollar weapons program 
it could very well shift the direction of the program away 
from modernization and toward cleanup he said 
watkins also won applause from capitol hill 
the departments decision today may mean that the bomb 
factories iron curtain of secrecy is lifting said rep les 
aucoin dore one of several members of congress who 13 months 
ago requested the environmental reviews 
many environmental groups including reichers have argued the 
government should spend more to clean up the trail of hazardous and 
radioactive wastes generated by weapons plants many of the 17 
major plants and laboratories in 12 states were built in the late 
1940s or early 1950s and operated for decades in a dome of secrecy 
that permitted environmental abuses 
watkins also announced friday he was sending independent teams 
of environmental specialists to five weapons plants or laboratories 
to study their compliance with federal and state environmental laws 
as well as health and safety rules 
the five plants are the savannah river site near aiken sc 
which makes materials for nuclear warheads the pinellas weapons 
components plant near largo fla the lawrence livermore national 
laboratory at livermore calif which performs research and 
testing of weapons designs the brookhaven nuclear research 
laboratory at upton ny and the sandia nuclear weapons 
laboratory at livermore 
watkins has been trying to reassure the public his department is 
committed to developing a longrange plan for cleaning up nuclear 
wastes but he also wants to spend billions of dollars rebuilding 
key parts of the weapons complex 
in his announcement watkins said the department would prepare 
an environmental impact statement on its recently published 
fiveyear plan for cleaning up the weapons plants he said the 
report will evaluate alternative approaches to resolving the waste 
problem including treatment storage and disposal options 
he said an environmental impact statement on longterm plans for 
modernizing the weapons production system also is planned although 
the department has not released details of a modernization plan 
catherine kaliniak a department spokeswoman said an internal 
assessment of modernization priorities will be completed in a few 
months 
watkins said public hearings would be held as part of the 
environmental studies and the results would be used as a 
planning tool to guide decision making 
preparation of these major environmental documents with 
opportunities for full public participation in the process will 
assure environmentally informed decision making he said 
</TEXT>
