<TEXT>
us computer companies are dropping plans for a 
cooperative venture to challenge japanese leadership in the making 
of computer memory chips according to published reports 
the proposed venture us memories failed to attract enough 
investors according to reports in saturdays editions of the new 
york times and the washington post citing sources in the computer 
industry 
the plan called for building a 1 billion factory to make 
computer memory chips using money donated by at least seven 
computer and semiconductor companies 
sanford l kane the president of us memories told the times 
that he was frustrated by his failure to persuade computer 
companies to sign up for the venture 
one can only bang their head against the wall for so long 
sooner or later you get a headache he told the times he refused 
to comment directly on the reports that the cooperative venture was 
dead 
us memories was announced in june as a project to restore 
american strength in production of the common computer memory chips 
known as dynamic random access memory chips or drams by november 
however several major computer companies including sun 
microsystems inc unisys corp apple computer inc and tandy 
corp had said they would not join as investors 
japanese firms supply a majority of the memory chips now 
available most american chip manufacturers dropped out of the 
market several years ago 
computer industry officials told the times that the end of us 
memories was decided wednesday at a meeting in dallas attended by 
the seven firms that had signed up and other firms still 
considering entering the venture 
the times said the project failed in part because the memory 
chips have become more widely available as samsung of south korea 
siemens ag of west germany and motorola inc of the united states 
have begun manufacturing the chips 
