<TEXT>
britains best ballet dancers are threatening to 
strike over pay and working conditions raising the prospect of a 
picket line outside the venerable royal opera house in covent 
garden 
the dispute had dragged on since july and now threatens the 
cancellation of three ballets it also has disrupted the first 
joint production of the royal opera and royal ballet the russian 
opera prince igor which has a 25minute ballet 
richard wright the royal opera administrator said friday that 
after two days talks with equity the performers labor union a 
revised offer would be made monday to the 136 dancers of the royal 
ballet and the sadlers wells royal ballet both share the royal 
opera house with the royal opera 
the opera house at first offered a 10 percent pay increase to 
the dancers demand for 15 percent the house gradually raised its 
offer to 15 percent but only in return for more hours of work and 
agreement to allow two productions a year to be shown on a screen 
to nonpaying crowds in the covent garden piazza 
the dancers are likely to go on saying no 
the dispute broke friday into frontpage caricature 
cartoonist matt of the conservative daily telegraph playing on 
a pay dispute at ford of britain auto plants showed one ford 
assemblyline worker saying to another i hope we dont go on 
strike i dont want people thinking im a ballet dancer 
the dancers want salaries that would close the gap with the 
higher pay of the choristers and musicians at the royal opera house 
the 15 percent offer would take the pay of senior principal 
dancers from 860 a week to 988 pay for firstyear members of the 
corps de ballet would go up from 278 to 322 for a 33hour week 
the dance dispute is really a rebellion at the 132yearold 
statesupported opera house where ballet dancers feel they have 
always been treated as poor cousins opera is definitely king at 
covent garden 
jeremy isaacs the opera house director struggling with a 5 
million deficit this year has pleaded for a quick settlement 
rebecca holmes 21 a royal ballet dancer of firstartist rank 
making 410 a week told a reporter her day usually runs from 7 
am to midnight with subway travel and having to use rehearsal 
rooms nearly six miles away from covent garden 
she said sunday is her one day off when all she does is sleep 
and eat 
the dancers say their work is tough and demanding with grueling 
rehearsals followed by evening performances their dancing careers 
will end in their mid30s 
friday also was a bad day for the royal ballet on another front 
anthony dowell the director said it had been forced to abandon 
talks with new yorks metropolitan opera association for a 
longplanned tour to the united states in july because it could not 
find sponsors 
i am very disappointed that the tour will not take place 
dowell said we were eagerly looking forward to a return visit to 
the metropolitan opera and to our american public 
