<TEXT>
people and wildlife in the great lakes region 
are exposed to a growing health threat because the us and 
canadian governments move too slowly in carrying out an 
antipollution plan environmentalists contend 
in a letter to secretary of state james baker iii and epa 
administrator william reilly a coalition of 10 environmental 
groups said failure to carry out the great lakes water quality 
agreement also is undermining us credibility in international 
environmental negotiations 
without action soon women in the great lakes basin may never 
be able to safely eat a fish dinner or nurse their children without 
fear of deadly pcb poisoning melanie griffin a sierra club 
official said at a news conference friday 
its as though the folks over there in the epa building dont 
even know that we have this treaty with canada said mark van 
putten director of the national wildlife federations great lakes 
natural resources center 
an epa official said the bush administration shares the 
environmentalists goals but added that implementing the agreement 
will take time 
because the problem is so big and complex and there are so 
many players involved things do not move with the speed of 
light said frank covington deputy administrator in the agencys 
chicago office headquarters of the epas great lakes program 
covington said epa has focused its attention on provisions added 
to the agreement in 1987 when the emphasis shifted to 40 hot 
spots where toxic pollution is especially severe the agency has 
been helping states develop plans for cleaning those areas he said 
signed in 1972 renewed in 1978 and updated two years ago the 
bilateral accord pledges the us and canadian governments to 
cooperate with each other in ridding the great lakes of toxic 
substances 
central to the pact is a pledge that toxic discharges into the 
waters be virtually eliminated 
there have been improvements since 1972 including cutbacks in 
the discharge of pollutants directly into the lakes ms griffin 
said but little has been done about toxins such as contaminated 
rainwater and runoff from farms city streets hazardous waste 
dumps and contaminated sediments she said 
numerous scientific studies have concluded the lake pollution is 
entering the food chain posing a health threat the 
environmentalists letter said 
researchers believe the atmosphere is the source of 25 percent 
of all toxins in the lakes ms griffin said yet the epa has 
regulated only seven of hundreds of toxic air pollutants she 
complained 
pesticides and phosphorus flow into the lakes from farm runoff 
and urban runoff contains heavy metals such as copper and lead 
said diane cameron an environmental engineer with the natural 
resources defense council 
the agreement calls for programs to collect and treat runoff 
which neither country has done adequately ms cameron said they 
also are failing to protect wetlands and continue to allow 
developers to construct buildings too close to lake shores 
worsening the runoff problem she said 
van putten said state and local governments in the great lakes 
region have added top the problem by engaging in a conspiracy of 
silence on covering up violations of regulations 
michigan is unwilling to publicly criticize wisconsin because 
