<TEXT>
romanians flush with the success of 
their uprising against nicolae ceausescu now face the formidable 
task of repairing the ravaged economy that is the former communist 
dictators legacy 
romanian economists and western experts say ceausescu severely 
restrained the economy by exporting goods needed at home and 
blocking imports that could have modernized the countrys 
antiquated industries 
the harsh program managed to pay off a 105 billion foreign 
debt but it also left romanian homes cold and people with only 
basic staples to eat 
how could one man do more than an economic tornado asked 
mircea pirjol spokesman for the provisional governments economy 
ministry 
for one romanias once healthy export trade in lathes has 
disappeared because the makers could not import modern calibration 
equipment said eugen dijmarescu a researcher at bucharests 
institute for world economy 
ironically the lack of foreign debt and the low production 
costs fostered by ceausescus policies could help revive the 
economy 
the dictator ousted dec 22 and executed three days later was 
replaced by an interim government headed by the national salvation 
front which plans to hold free elections as early as april 
the countrys immediate need is for help in providing food and 
heating for romanias 23 million people during the long harsh 
winter the soviet union already has promised fuel oil and the 
united states and france have said they are working on aid programs 
pirjol says economists trying to solve longrange problems must 
first find out exactly where the country stands since most economic 
statistics from ceausescus 24 years in power cannot be trusted 
asked about production figures pirjol replied god knows all 
the economic data was falsified 
one example is grain production before ceausescu was toppled 
dec 22 the government reported a 1989 harvest of 60 million tons 
the provisional government recently said the real figure was 169 
million tons 
dijmarescu said industrial production figures were just as 
uncertain 
last year ceausescu said that onethird of industrial capacity 
was not properly employed if he said that you can imagine the 
problem is much greater said dijmarescu whose private institute 
has been hired by the goverment to help plan romanias economic 
future 
a western diplomatic source who spoke on condition of 
anonymity estimated that less than 5 percent of romanias industry 
was working at capacity 
dijmarescu said that not all romanias economic problems could 
be blamed on ceausescu 
communist policies before his time devastated the oncerich farm 
economy by driving peasants into cities for jobs in industry and 
collectivizing what had been profitable small farms 
but ceausescu held to his policy of expanding heavy industry and 
developing grandiose projects when other east bloc countries 
recognized the need for new trade policies 
for the past five years 60 percent of the countrys meat was 
sent abroad homes and factories were kept cold and dimly lighted 
so petroleum products could be exported 
at the same time virtually all imports were blocked 
this did more than leave consumers crying for western goods it 
denied modern technology to factories and meant romanian goods were 
without the imported components that could have made them saleable 
ceausescu announced last april that romania had succeeded in 
wiping out the 1982 foreign debt of 105 billion but he did not 
withdraw austerity measures perhaps raising the public anger that 
brought his downfall in fact food rationing was expanded in 
october 
dijmarescu says the first needs are to revive agriculture and 
upgrade industrial technology 
for years people in this county have been in a black hole in 
terms of knowledge he said we need an inflow of economic and 
scientific information we need to train people to manage a market 
economy 
the western diplomatic source said it will not be possible to 
privatize some of romanias huge heavy industries for years 
one of the countrys assets could be its agriculture already 
being pushed by a decision of the interim government to give land 
to peasants another plus could be light industry such as 
textiles and shoes if technology in factories can be upgraded 
quickly 
dijmarescu warned that romania will have to avoid economic 
shocks that could lead to social tensions he noted that one dated 
heavy equipment factory has 20000 workers and added you cant 
just close down a factory with that many employees 
