<TEXT>
even before the article was published the 
foreign policy establishment and the academic world were abuzz 
when it appeared copies of a highbrow journal with a slender 
circulation were suddenly in high demand 
the article in daedalus was about ussoviet relations and it 
was signed with the provocative pseudonym z a clear allusion 
to the 1947 article signed x that laid the theoretical 
framework for the cold war policy of containment 
xs article published in the journal foreign affairs later was 
acknowledged to be the work of george f kennan a state department 
official who later became ambassador to the soviet union and one of 
the nations leading diplomats 
speculation about the identity of z began last thursday when 
excerpts from the daedalus article appeared on the opinion page of 
the new york times washington was soon alive with rumors that the 
author was a wellplaced government official perhaps even a 
wellplaced soviet government official 
the article takes a dim view of mikhail gorbachevs chances of 
making the soviet system economically efficient and politically 
democratic while maintaining the primacy of the communist party 
the fundamental structures of the leninist system reached an 
inextricable impasse at the end of the 1970s and the mounting 
contradictions of perestroika indicate that the system cannot be 
restructured or reformed but can only stagnate or be dismantled 
and replaced by market institutions over a long period of time z 
wrote 
daedalus a literary and philosophical quarterly published by 
the 210yearold american academy of arts and sciences in 
cambridge mass printed 23000 copies of todays edition 3000 
more than usual and expects to issue many reprints said its 
editor stephen graubard 
graubard however was hardly ecstatic about his publishing 
coup instead the 65yearold editor was ruminating about the 
frivolity of the american media and fuming about allegations 
that the pseudonym was hype 
i want people to read it and say whether they agree or 
disagree graubard said in a telephone interview this is a 
very serious subject and so far i have yet to see an analysis of 
what was said as opposed to a guessing game about who said it 
graubard refused to name the author or explain why a pseudonym 
was used except to say that there were compelling reasons to 
protect the writers identity 
as to the allegation by columnist patrick buchanan that the z 
byline was just clever hype graubard was indignant 
all you have to do is read daedalus to know we dont go in for 
hype he said 
z argues that it is futile for the united states to try to help 
gorbachev succeed in his avowed aims of democratizing the communist 
system and revitalizing the soviet economy 
but the article contends the west can play a constructive role 
primarily by investing in the soviet unions emerging private 
sector without triumphalism about capitalisms superiority and 
with due sensitivity to soviet national pride 
the wests aim should be to encourage the change of soviet 
realities while leaving the old labels intact the article says 
the arkansas democrat reported today that it had determined z 
was retired lt gen william odom the former director of the 
national security agency the newspaper quoted william e jackson 
jr an international relations professor at the university of 
arkansas as saying odom a close friend was z 
odom reached friday in middlebury vt gave a cryptic 
response he denied that he was z but said the newspapers 
reporter would be correct in quoting jackson 
you can write what he says said odom who in september was 
quoted as warning that it was unlikely a liberal democracy would be 
established in the soviet union and that reforms there could lead 
to chaos 
much of the speculation about zs identity has focused on robert 
m gates president bushs deputy national security adviser 
gates had planned to give a speech late last year expressing 
pessimism about gorbachevs chances of success but was blocked by 
secretary of state james a baker iii who reportedly felt such 
sentiments were inappropriate about the time of the malta summit 
gates denied through the white house press office on friday that 
he is z 
another possible author is zbigniew brzezinski former national 
security adviser under president carter brzezinski declined to 
discuss the article but did not expressly deny writing it 
new york times writer flora lewis suggested in her column today 
that z was dennis ross head of the state departments policy 
planning staff 
after the original x article appeared in july 1947 kennan 
was identified as the author within a matter of days now a 
historian at the institute for advanced studies in princeton nj 
kennan declined to discuss the z article 
graubard said he believes zs article is infinitely more 
provocative than the mr x article was in its day but not all 
scholars agreed 
the sense of it is that we should help the russians right now 
but whether gorbachev succeeds or fails is going to be decided 
inside the soviet union said adam ulam director of the russian 
research center at harvard university its a sensible but not 
terribly original point of view 
</TEXT>
