the air force is proposing to retire all 450 
minuteman 2 intercontinental ballistic missiles at a savings of 
400 million a year a newspaper reported today 
defense secretary dick cheney has tentatively accepted the 
proposal the washington post said and will discuss it with 
congressional leaders next week before making a final decision 
a defense department spokesman air force lt col richard 
oborn said late friday that he had no information on the matter 
the newspaper quoted unnamed officials who cautioned that 
president bush might withdraw the proposal before he presents his 
fiscal year 1991 budget to congress on jan 29 
meanwhile cheney on friday ordered a freeze on hiring civilians 
at the defense department for the rest of this fiscal year cheney 
said in a statement he took the step to cut costs and because of 
sweeping international changes 
the release announcing the step cautioned that department 
officials do not know how much the work force will be reduced by 
the freeze 
in effect until sept 30 the hiring freeze applies to all 
department of defense civilians worldwide including parttime and 
temporary employees the department currently employs 927000 
civilians fulltime and another 123000 on a temporary or parttime 
as many as 80000 workers normally retire or otherwise leave 
that work force each year the pentagon said 
the minuteman 2 based at malmstrom air force base mont 
ellsworth air force base sd and whiteman air force base mo 
carries a single warhead with an explosive force estimated at 12 
megatons or the equivalent of 12 million tons of tnt that is 80 
times the power of the atomic bomb that destroyed the japanese city 
of hiroshima in 1945 
these are the last warheads in the us arsenal greater than one 
megaton in destructive power 
compared with later missiles the minuteman 2 is relatively 
inaccurate published estimates say half the missiles launched 
would land within 1200 feet to 2000 feet of the point of aim 
similar estimates for the 550 deployed minuteman 3 missiles 
which carry three smaller warheads are from 600 feet to 700 feet 
in addition to the minuteman the nations landbased missiles 
include 50 mx peacekeeper missiles with 10 warheads each 
counting other missiles and bombs the minuteman 2 force represents 
about 35 percent of the nations strategic nuclear warheads 
the bush administration has proposed building a new 
midgetman singlewarhead missile that could be moved about on 
giant trucks much more difficult to hit than known fixed 
positions such as current minuteman silos 
because they are so old and inaccurate the minuteman 2 missiles 
have been candidates for retirement for some time the 
administration told congress last summer that a likely strategic 
nuclear arms treaty with the soviet union would mean significant 
reductions in missiles on both sides 
