<TEXT>
two allies of former philippines ruler ferdinand 
marcos were found liable in the murders of two cannery union 
members and ordered to pay their survivors at least 84 million 
us district judge barbara rothstein found conclusive evidence 
friday that constantine tony baruso and leonilo malabed drew 
from a fund established to battle marcos opponents in the united 
states to arrange the deaths of silme domingo and gene viernes 
slain in the seattle offices of the alaska cannery workers union in 
1981 
this is wonderful said jeff robinson one of the attorneys 
for the families 
rothsteins ruling awarded 6669000 to the estate of domingo 
and 1727800 to viernes survivors with a pain and suffering 
portion to be decided later 
malabeds attorney kate alfieri of san francisco said she 
would appeal the ruling barusos attorney anthony savage of 
seattle could not be reached for comment 
baruso was president of the union when the killings occurred 
although his gun was used in the shootings he was never criminally 
charged 
malabed allegedly ran marcos west coast intelligence operation 
and controlled a slush fund for security projects against 
marcos opponents 
his testimony vacillated between a total lack of memory and 
outright fabrication said rothstein who concluded malabeds 
fund provided baruso 15000 for the murders 
baruso was found liable for conspiracy to monitor harass 
intimidate and operate against marcos opponents while malabed was 
found liable for the conspiracy charge and for negligence for not 
keeping the intelligence operations in check 
the late marcos and his wife imelda were found liable on dec 
15 for running an intelligence network that spied on foes of his 
regime they were ordered to pay 15 million to the families of 
domingo and viernes marcos was ousted as president of the 
philippines in 1986 and fled to hawaii where he died in september 
michael withey lead attorney for the plaintiffs said he would 
meet monday with king county prosecutor norm maleng about reopening 
a criminal investigation of the case 
three men were convicted in 1981 and 1982 of murdering domingo 
and viernes but those trials did not conclude the existence of a 
marcoslinked conspiracy although testimony indicated baruso 
traveled to san francisco and picked up 15000 from a philippines 
intelligence fund to pay for the killings 
malabed in depositions admitted he maintained a fund through 
the mabuhay corp from which he made payments to a philippines 
official for broadcast projects in this country he maintained 
that he did not know specifically where that money went 
malabed also admitted he signed a mabuhay expense account that 
listed several special security projects including a may 17 
1981 entry for 15000 that plaintiffs claimed was used to pay for 
the murders 
baruso denied he knew malabed but rothstein said she found the 
plaintiffs presented overwhelming evidence that baruso was directly 
involved in the murders of domingo and viernes 
she said baruso promised to pay 5000 to the killers and that 
the murder weapon was barusos 
the civil trial had a lower standard of proof than the beyond 
a reasonable doubt proof required in criminal trials the 
conspiracy count required a showing of clear cogent and 
convincing evidence and the negligence count a showing of a 
preponderance of evidence 
