<TEXT>
a couple who sued the navy over the loss of 
their cattle ranch have found it difficult to prove that the 
thousands of jets screaming overhead are what caused their cows to 
lose their enthusiasm for breeding 
don and barbara nonella sued the navy for 87 million claiming 
flights out of the fallon naval air station ruined their business 
and drove them off the land which they couldnt sell and the navy 
wouldnt buy don nonella now drives trucks out of elko in eastern 
nevada 
the couple claims that increased jet training activity over 
their ranch 60 miles east of the naval air station killed some of 
their cattle and caused other cows to reproduce less 
but the navys laywer lt mike quinn said friday the couple 
had failed to prove their claim 
things happen that only god can explain quinn said 
fluctuations in production are normal and to be expected theres 
no evidence to suggest that noise did it 
bob alexander who represents the couple said he had proved the 
cattle were not diseased and were fed properly ruling out 
everything but stress from the earpopping sonic booms caused by 
the jets to explain why the cows were not reproducing 
closing arguments in the fiveday trial ended friday and it was 
left in the hands of us district judge bruce thompson 
quinn said the nonellas ranch lay beneath both a military 
operations area and a supersonic flight range and with more than 
64000 flights out of the naval air station each year in the late 
1980s it was logical there would be noise 
the pilots must train somewhere and that somewhere is central 
nevada clearly our operation at times affects the people of 
central nevada they bear part of the burden of making sure our 
nation is prepared he said 
alexander argued that the nonellas would have had 1 million in 
livestock sales each year from 1985 to 1988 if production hadnt 
dropped off but quinn said the couple bought the ranch when cattle 
prices were high and interest rates were low then lost it as 
livestock prices declined and interest rates rose 
the couple said the conception rate of cows on their property 
was more than 90 percent from 1979 when they bought the ranch but 
fell to about 67 percent after 1984 they left the land in may 1988 
james cothern an agricultural economics professor at the 
university of california in fresno and davis testified that a 
computer analysis he performed showed the ranch was just 
accumulating debt and would have failed no matter what 
nonella 58 disputed that outside the courtroom 
you dont run a ranch by computer you run it by the seat of 
your pants he said patting the bottom of his blue jeans 
a government expert testified that cattle might become startled 
and even run a bit when fasterthansound military jets fly 
overhead to set off sonic booms but the animals arent adversely 
affected by the noise 
