<TEXT>
in order to build a series of 
hydroelectric dams turkey today cut the flow of the eurphrates 
river to syria and iraq in a move that could cause problems for the 
two arid nations over the next month 
invoking the name of allah president turgut ozal pushed a 
button that closed the hatches of the giant ataturk dam the action 
will allow engineers to fill a reservoir to a height of 396 feet 
and build a concrete plug for a diversion channel as part of the 
construction project 
during the onemonth stoppage syria and iraq will get less 
water from the tributaries of the euphrates the river that has 
been the lifeblood throughout history for the area that once formed 
ancient mesopotamia 
the ceremony today was a moment of pride and accomplishment for 
turkey which views the southeast anatolia project to build more 
than a dozen dams as the key to the economic development of the 
backward region 
but the event is considered a cause for worry for iraq and 
syria which are highly dependent on the waters of the 1460mile 
euphrates river it was the lifeblood of ancient mesopotamia a 
part of modernday iraq 
for one month syria and iraq will receive about onefourth of 
the water they normally get from the tributaries of the euphrates 
turkey said that since november it has released extra water to 
syria and iraq to allow them to store water in reservoirs for use 
during the cutoff 
syria has made no statement on the water stoppage iraq sent its 
