has agreed to free 50 disabled iranian pows clearing the way for 
the first prisoner exchange between the two countries in more than 
a year 
peace talks between iran and iraq have been stalled almost since 
they began in august 1988 and the deadlock has left an estimated 
100000 captives on both sides languishing in pow camps some have 
been held since the early stages of the war which began in 
september 1980 
the international committee of the red cross said 50 iranian 
pows will be released and returned to iran after iran returns 50 
iraqi prisoners to baghdad 
irans un ambassador kamal kharrazi announced in new york 
last week that iran would release the ailing iraqis 
the iraqi authorities have promised to reciprocate with the 
release of an equal number of pows a red cross official said 
saturday 
the iraqis are scheduled to be set free wednesday said the 
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity they said a swiss 
airliner had been chartered to fly the iraqis home 
un officials have registered 55000 pows held by iran and 
19500 by iraqi but they believe the total held by both sides is 
about 100000 both sides hold a total of about 1000 ailing or 
disabled prisoners 
the 1948 geneva convention stipulates that all prisoners of war 
should be released when hostilities cease 
a ceasefire halted fighting between iran and iraq in august 
1988 but the pows have become pawns as both sides quarrel over 
details of the un resolution that cleared the way for the 
ceasefire 
in 1988 the two sides exchanged about 400 disabled and ailing 
prisoners the operation collapsed in november of that year as each 
country accused the other of lying about the number of captives 
they held 
this month iraqi president saddam hussein offered to restart 
the peace talks and said iraq was ready to exchange all disabled 
and sick prisoners as a first step toward a total prisoner exchange 
iran countered that it would not agree to total swap or to 
implement other clauses of the ceasefire resolution until iraq 
withdrew from iranian border areas captured during the final days 
of fighting 
but iranian officials have expressed support for a soviet offer 
to mediate a new round of peace talks 
the soviets have close links with iraq and were its main arms 
supplier during the war relations between moscow and tehran have 
improved considerably since the war ended 
iranian foreign minister ali akbar velayati said tehran would 
consider any soviet proposal containing a systematic and clearly 
defined formula for the implementation of un security council 
resolution 598 the ceasefire resolution 
the iraqi foreign ministry also welcomed the soviet offer 
