<TEXT>
cuba continues to be an important military and 
intelligence asset for the soviet union and the longstanding 
moscowhavana alliance is expected to survive deepening ideological 
differences according to analysts 
there is little question that the relationship is far less 
relaxed than it was before soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
assumed power but the consensus among experts is that cuba is too 
valuable for the soviets to cast aside 
still as us officials see it there is evidence of a decline 
in soviet assistance to cuba a trend that may continue but not to 
the point where the survival of the regime is threatened one 
example of the strength of the relationship was the recent delivery 
of soviet mig29 jet fighters to cuba the officials say 
says cornell university professor rhoda rabkin there is 
little sign that the gorbachev era leadership considers cuba an 
expendable soviet commitment 
among other assets she notes the soviets have an extensive 
electronic intelligence gathering facility in cuba and 
installations that enable soviet longrange reconnaissance aircraft 
to monitor us east coast military activities thanks to cuba the 
soviets also are able to maintain a strategic naval presence in the 
caribbean 
professor jaime suchlicki of the university of miamis institute 
of interamerican studies points out that these soviet activities 
have forced the united states to install expensive surveillance and 
tracking facilities to keep an eye on the soviets 
gillian gunn an associate at the carnegie endowment for 
international peace a washington research group says soviet 
leaders have been cool to us admonitions that they distance 
themselves from castro 
gorbachev has left the impression he opposes castros effort to 
promote subversion in the hemisphere but the soviets have told 
us officials privately they have no way of knowing how castro 
would react if they pushed him too hard according to ms gunn 
if they tinker with his aid he could mess around with their 
military access she says summing up soviet concerns 
soviet bloc arms continue to find their way to central america 
via cuba but the bush administration is more inclined to blame 
havana than moscow 
uncertainty about sovietcuban relations has arisen as a result 
of castros repudiation of perestroika and glasnost and gorbachevs 
willingness to nudge hardline regimes from power in eastern europe 
a strain in relations was evident last summer when castro banned 
two soviet spanishlanguage publications because he was offended by 
their irreverent comments about socialism castro has said that 
death is preferable to abandonment of socialism 
us officials say there is one area in which soviet aid to cuba 
appears to have dried up the soviets used to provide cuba with 
surplus oil enabling castro to sell the commodity at world market 
prices for a handsome profit 
according to the economist newsletter revenues from oil exports 
reached 621 million in 1985 and then fell sharply last year the 
earnings were almost certainly nothing it said 
gorbachev has called for stricter accountability in the way 
cuba uses soviet aid estimated at 43 billion by us officials 
no recipient of us aid gets nearly as much 
one official said that given gorbachevs emphasis on improving 
living standards in the soviet union he would like to reduce his 
economic burden in cuba further but not to be point where the 
survivability of the regime comes into doubt 
one test of the durability of the sovietcuban relationship will 
come next year when payments on cubas substantial soviet debt 
estimated at 10 billion fall due 
it is widely expected that cuba will ask for lenient terms just 
how accommodating the soviets will be remains a question mark 
