<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev said 
saturday he no longer objects to the legalization of multiple 
political parties in the soviet union where his communist party 
has held a monopoly on power for 72 years 
i see no tragedy in a multiparty system if and i can tell 
you this straightforwardly it arises as a result of a normal 
historical process and answers the needs of society gorbachev 
told lithuanias communist party 
it was a surprising reversal by gorbachev who had remained 
opposed to the idea of rival political parties even as 
prodemocracy movements forced an end to oneparty communist rule 
elsewhere in eastern europe 
soviet police routinely have broken up demonstrations by the 
democratic union until recently the only soviet organization 
trying to establish itself as an opposition party 
a reason for gorbachevs turnaround could be that multiparty 
systems already exist in lithuania and latvia the party ideology 
chief in the third baltic republic estonia has said the same is 
inevitable there 
lithuania was the first to legalize other political parties and 
lithuanian communists will face them in february elections to the 
lithuanian parliament 
gorbachev came to the baltic republic in an effort to persuade 
the lithuanian communist party to reverse its decision last month 
to break with the central communist party 
the threeday visit ended with the lithuanians refusing to 
budge the president concluded saturdays party meeting with the 
statement we have laid a good foundation for continuing the 
dialogue he then returned to moscow 
gorbachev pleaded for unity in both the party and the soviet 
union but faced proindependence demonstrators at every stop and 
clearly had no significant effect on public opinion 
lithuanians strongly support independence for the republic 
which was forcibly annexed in 1940 while occupied by the red army 
the communist party ideology chief vadim a medvedev told a 
news conference after the meeting that elaboration on gorbachevs 
statement on multiple parties will be contained in an article 
written by gorbachev and due to appear in the soviet press 
possibly as early as sunday 
communists have held exclusive power in the soviet union since a 
few months after the 1917 russian revolution a number of parties 
operated in the last years of the czars reign but had little 
power and a number competed for control during the turbulent year 
of revolution itself 
gorbachevs statement was the first indication the soviet union 
might catch up with the wave of political reform that has been 
sweeping eastern europe in recent months 
poland east germany hungary and romania have all eliminated 
the communists guaranteed hold on political power and either 
formed multiparty systems or scheduled free elections 
gorbachev has made clear his willingness to end the communists 
legal guarantee on political power codified in the soviet 
constitution but until now he expressed scorn for a multiparty 
system 
on friday he told an audience in siauliai lithuania havent 
you and i seen and known during our long life that even with 10 or 
20 parties the most cruel dictatorships formed and flourished 
and will a multiparty system save society no it is the 
regime that determines who lives how and who breathes how 
gorbachevs reversal was his second surprising announcement on 
the lithuanian tour on thursday he said a law was being drafted 
to set up a mechanism for republics to secede from the soviet union 
he promised that the lithuanian people would be allowed to 
choose their own fate and predicted they would remain in the union 
once they realize the financial costs and human dislocation that 
secession would cause 
in a long speech to the lithuanian communists gorbachev said 
separatists were in too much of a hurry 
think a thousand times before embarking on an independent 
drift without a compass without a map a fuel reserve or a 
competent crew he said 
in a lecturing tone gorbachev also warned there is no 
absolute freedom and you wont find absolute independence 
anywhere everything in the world is interrelated 
lithuanian communist party chief algirdas brazauskas said in his 
speech that events forced his party to split with the national 
communist party 
comprehensive analysis of the political situation throughout 
the republic convinced us that only an independent communist party 
could hold the trust of the residents of lithuania and only on 
that basis could it remain a serious political force he said 
in the end gorbachev invited the breakaway lithuanians to the 
next national party congress in october implying the meeting might 
adopt enough reforms to bring them back into the fold 
the invitation might be to gorbachevs advantage since the 
lithuanians are likely to back him against conservative opponents 
in the congress 
