<TEXT>
tens of thousands of ambulance workers and their 
backers rallied with banners and a brass band saturday to support 
pay demands of the emergency crews in an 18weekold dispute with 
the government 
london ambulance workers who earn 16906 a year after five 
years at work began job actions more than four months ago they 
were suspended on nov 8 and replaced by police and military staff 
when they decided not to respond to nonemergency calls 
although management stopped putting emergency calls through to 
the ambulance workers in many cases the depots remained staffed 
and unpaid crews responded to such calls from hospitals or fire 
stations 
the pay dispute spread through the country and on thursday 60 
workers in west sussex county south of london went on unofficial 
strike 
the death of a man in that district saturday received wide news 
coverage when it was announced it had taken 31 minutes for a fully 
equipped ambulance to reach him 
an estimated 15000 ambulance crew members and their families 
marched saturday along whitehall and into trafalgar square to 
cheers and applause from crowds estimated at 15000 or more 
the march which included banners a brass band and young 
children lent a carnival atmosphere to the government center of 
the capital 
a police inspector said it was one of the biggest rallies held 
in london for many years we could not fit everyone into the 
square so people are packed onto surrounding pavements he said 
ambulance workers have demanded an 11 percent raise and a pay 
formula like those of police and firemen guaranteeing automatic 
raises the government has offered an increase of 9 percent over 18 
months but it says it wont accept the pay formula 
