<TEXT>
the first surgeon to implant the jarvik 
artificial heart says he might use it again if a patients life 
were threatened even though the food and drug administration has 
withdrawn its approval 
i have an option of either disobeying the law and helping a 
dying patient or letting the patient die because im scared of 
what the fda will do to me said dr william c devries 
if it comes to a matter of you getting slapped on your wrist 
and saving a patients life youd rather get slapped on the 
wrist 
the fda said last week it was withdrawing approval of the 
devices use after inspections revealed serious deficiencies in 
the way symbion inc the jarviks manufacturer was carrying out 
studies with the device 
the fda cited shortcomings in quality control researchsite 
monitoring training of personnel and reporting of adverse 
reactions 
devries said friday he believes the jarvik is scientifically a 
sound device and it keeps people alive that would normally die 
he would refuse to use the device if he found problems affecting 
the quality of the artificial heart he added 
but i dont intend to have my patients suffer because i dont 
have a device available the louisvillebased surgeon said 
the head of the transplant and artificialheart program at the 
university of arizona dr jack copeland also said last week he 
would consider continued use of the artificial heart because he 
believes there is no scientific basis for the fdas decision 
devries said he asked the fda what he should do about carl e 
bryant a suburban louisville man who received a jarvik 770 on 
dec 22 as a bridge to a heart transplant he said the fda told 
him you go ahead with what youre doing 
devries said the jarvik has been used by 37 clinical 
investigators and implanted as a bridge to a transplant more than 
150 times making it one of the leading devices being used to buy 
time for patients who need heart transplants 
devries was the only surgeon in the united states authorized by 
the fda to perform permanent implants of artificial hearts 
he implanted the jarvik7 into the chests of barney clark the 
worlds first artificial heart patient william schroeder murray 
haydon and jack burcham schroeder of jasper ind lived 620 days 
after receiving his jarvik7 nov 25 1984 becoming the longest 
living receipient of the artificial heart 
the last permanent artificial heart recipient was burcham who 
died 10 days after the implant on april 14 1985 
devries artificial heart research is funded by humana inc a 
louisvillebased healthcare chain that lured him from the 
university of utah several years ago devries said humana supports 
his intention to explore the possibility of using other mechanical 
assist devices as well the jarvik 
but the surgeon notes it would take months to gain the 
necessary approval to switch 
humanas commitment is to research on artificial hearts and 
mechanical assist devices not to the jarvik specifically said 
company spokeswoman susan mcarthur 
