<TEXT>
american investors soon might be asked to change 
their personalities to think long term rather than short term to 
invest rather than trade to be patient rather than excited and 
expectant 
its a large order similar in ways to asking a junkie to get 
off the stuff it can be done but it will take lots of time and 
enormous willpower with great temptations and failures along the 
way 
since the 1960s at least americans have been weaned on the 
dreams of quick returns by brokers analysts advisers tipsters 
letterwriters the media and tax laws with enough success 
stories to make it seem the way to go 
you might even add that the proliferation of state lotteries has 
added to the shortterm speculative easy money gambling 
mentality 
oldtime brokers and advisers who taught the other ways were 
left in the shadows their techniques required effort choose 
quality understand the company reinvest dividends be prepared to 
wait five years for a good return 
they warned that inout trading was foolish because the 
temptation to sell was great when the stock was at the bottom and 
to buy when the stock was near the top you cant win that way 
they said besides commissions will kill you 
but they were up against something bigger than they could 
handle whenever people talked about the market somebody would tell 
the story of a friend who made a fortune on a tip of shoeshine 
boys who hit it big of easy money 
besides the big investors were inout traders and look how 
they lived it didnt matter that they were featured in magazines 
only when they hit it big disappearing from view when they lost 
it people love winners not losers 
every day the newspaper brought more excitement featuring the 
winners and how they did it with interpretations and broker 
forecasts of bigger things to come brokers like lots of action 
because action makes commissions 
the shortterm mentality is now pervasive not just in 
securities markets but in attitudes about how to run institutions 
of every sort including the family corporations and the federal 
government 
for millions of families instant gratification was made 
possible by easy credit and until recent years the cost of that 
credit was taxdeductible uncle sam succumbed too he maintained 
his lifestyle with foreign debt 
corporate executives might have wished to think longterm and 
build their companies for the future but to do so might have cut 
into shortterm profits and so they asked what will wall street 
think 
they still might want to invest funds in research and 
development to make a stronger company in the future but if 
shareholders expect dividends now how do you convince them that it 
is better to wait a few years 
some executives are in a different situation they want to spend 
today for a stronger tomorrow but they dont have the wherewithal 
their predecessor borrowed to make acquisitions and interest 
payments now take every nickel available 
bush administration officials especially treasury secretary 
nicholas f brady have indicated they would like to focus on the 
longer term but it will take a massive effort and that effort in 
itself will be long term 
among other things theyve suggested a family savings 
account where interest would accumulate taxfree a taxreduction 
for longterm capital gains would of that nature too but any such 
proposal still faces opposition 
perhaps the most convincing technique of all is to find ways of 
emphasizing the great returns that come from patient longterm 
investing in effect of teaching that time is as important in 
investing as interest rates 
in time and assuming investors do their homework it is 
difficult not to make money in an economy that keeps growing its 
all in the numbers as they say 
in every decade but two in this century the stock market has 
made solid gains far in excess of the inflation rate that is the 
gains were real in terms of spendable income except for the 
1930s and 70s 
in the past 90 years according to wright investors service 
stocks have provided a compound average annual return of 98 
percent or triple the annual inflation rate of 32 percent 
at that rate investments double every seven years and if 
theyre left to double again and again well thats how fortunes 
are made 
