<TEXT>
it is a fundamental of economics that when supplies of 
commodities tighten prices rise 
the market for winter wheat may prove another classic case with 
lower than expected plantings threatening to push up prices 
the verdict is already in for floridas orange producers the 
december freeze was more devastating than 1983 and production could 
be slashed to the levels of the mid1960s 
farmers planted about 57 million acres of winter wheat for 
harvest this year up 3 percent from the previous crop according 
to a us department of agriculture report released thursday 
winter wheat is planted in the fall and harvested the following 
year it accounts for about threefourths of the total us wheat 
output 
two years of drought shrunk the nations wheat stockpile to 142 
billion bushels on dec 1 down 17 percent from dec 1 1988 
according to the usda that makes us supplies at their tightest 
since the early 1970s 
a lingering drought in the southern plains states apparently 
caused farmers to plant less acreage than they had the previous 
fall an unexpected development 
dale gustafson an analyst with drexel burnham lambert inc in 
chicago said the lingering dryness in pockets of the plains may 
have already adversely affected the size of the winter wheat crop 
gustafson said the tight supplies and smaller than expected 
planting could result in a bullish market for wheat 
that is something we are not going to know until we find out 
the status of the new crop he said we dont know the extent 
of the weather kill and we dont know what the moisture will be 
gustafson said the wheat inventory could remain tight and the 
market could turn bullish if the weather is uncooperative 
the usda estimated the 1989 corn crop at 75 billion bushels 
which was below expectations and soybean production at 19 billion 
bushels also lower than expected 
the weathers impact on floridas orange crop is already known 
the usda has slashed the 198990 orange harvest by 29 percent 
once projected before the december cold wave at only 130 million 
90pound boxes is now 92 million boxes the smallest estimated 
production since the 196465 season 
the orange crop last season was 146 million boxes 
